I used optimization as a scapegoat here, when what I really meant was "use the API that gives you the guarantees you want";  Apologies.  

get_if says, "get me this type or nullptr" which is not the operation you're doing on the right.  When we get the clang-tidy stuff here, we'll get automatic CI about implicit conversion to bool, but for the moment, it's by hand.

as a practice:

if (std::holds_alternative<type>(foo)){
   return;
}
foo myFoo= std::get<type>(foo);

is accessing the foo object twice, and attempting to pull our the type twice, which is harder to reason about.  It requires the maintainer to think about "ok, std::get throws, where are they catching the throw?" then realize that it can't throw, and hopefully, the throw and the type check are close enough together that the compiler can optimize out the throw.   If instead, you did

foo* myFoo = std::get_if<type>(foo);
if (myFoo == nullptr){
   return;
}
You've asked for exactly what you want, checked, and handle the error without relying on any thinking.


With all of this said, the holds_alternative pattern was there before, which I can live with, and unless I'm missing something, doesn't have anything to do wtih the change in this patchset., but if we're going to change it, we should change it to something better

